{"Body": "<!-- p.p1 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; text-align: justify; font: 9.0px 'Whitney HTF SemiBold'} p.p2 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 10.0px 0.0px; text-align: justify; font: 9.0px 'Whitney HTF'} p.p3 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; text-align: justify; text-indent: 10.0px; font: 9.0px 'Utopia Std'} span.s1 {font: 9.0px 'Whitney HTF'; letter-spacing: -0.1px} span.s2 {letter-spacing: -0.2px} span.s3 {letter-spacing: -0.1px} -->By Barra Roantree -\u00a0College Affairs Correspondent\n\nThe publication of the Hunt drew a wide range of responses from various groups, many represented on the committee which drew up the report. Launching the report, Minister for Education (and Health) Mary Coughlan said the report was &ldquo;the future blueprint for the sector&rdquo; and was necessary given the prediction &ldquo;the number of students seeking higher education will increase by 70% in the next two decades&rdquo;.\n\nThe Irish Universities Association (IUA) welcomed the report as setting out &ldquo;a strategic framework for the development of Higher Education&rdquo;. They echoed the &ldquo;proposal to develop a system of income contingent loans&rdquo; and for expansion of participation to focus mainly on &ldquo;part time and adult learners, post graduate and international students&rdquo;.\n\nThe College noted that the contents of the report had not been &ldquo;formally discussed by College fora yet&rdquo;, referring the University Times to the statement by the (IUA).\u00a0 &ldquo;many of the recommendations have already been implemented by Trinity already&rdquo;.\n\nStudent reaction was more hostile, with the Union of Students in Ireland saying the recommendations in the report would &ldquo;lead to brain drain and reduction in access to education&rdquo;. Gary Redmond, USI president said while he welcomed many of the recommendations relating to part-time students and standards of teaching, &ldquo;the proposal for a student loan scheme is unworkable, unfeasible and if it is implemented, it will be a regressive step for this country, and will in fact lead to increased exchequer borrowing&rdquo;.\n\nJennifer Fox, education officer for Trinity Students&rsquo; Union, said that &ldquo;while a large amount of the report was positive, there are fundamental flaws linked to a number of the recommendations. I don&rsquo;t believe it was unplanned that many of the progressive suggestions in the report are vague while funding changes are specific.&rdquo;\n\nUnions for staff in third level institutions were more equivocal in their response. IFUT, the Irish Federation of University Teachers welcomed the call for a substantial increase in funding for higher education, but called the report &ldquo;uninspiring&rdquo;.\u00a0 With a change in government imminent, IFUT remarked that &ldquo;Colin Hunt and his team may well have created one of our all-time most expensive dust accumulators&rdquo;\n\nFine Gael said the report illustrated the failures of successive Fianna F\u00e1il governments. Education spokesperson Fergus O&rsquo;Dowd TD claimed Fine Gael were the &ldquo;only political party to set out a comprehensive strategy for reforming third level&rdquo;, and reiterated his party&rsquo;s support for a graduate tax.\n\nRuair\u00ed Quinn TD, Labour spokesperson on education, said the delay in the publication of the report &ldquo;is sadly indicative of the lack of urgency within the Department of Education and Skills to confront a range of important issues&rdquo;. He condemned the report&rsquo;s recommendations on undergraduate fees, saying the conclusions were &ldquo;vague, poorly described, not quantified in any manner and would receive a D mark if submitted as an answer to a Commerce Degree exam&rdquo;.", "Imageurl": "<!-- p.p1 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; text-align: justify; font: 9.0px 'Whitney HTF SemiBold'} p.p2 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 10.0px 0.0px; text-align: justify; font: 9.0px 'Whitney HTF'} p.p3 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; text-align: justify; text-indent: 10.0px; font: 9.0px 'Utopia Std'} span.s1 {font: 9.0px 'Whitney HTF'; letter-spacing: -0.1px} span.s2 {letter-spacing: -0.2px} span.s3 {letter-spacing: -0.1px} -->By Barra Roantree -\u00a0College Affairs Correspondent\n\nThe publication of the Hunt drew a wide range of responses from various groups, many represented on the committee which drew up the report. Launching the report, Minister for Education (and Health) Mary Coughlan said the report was &ldquo;the future blueprint for the sector&rdquo; and was necessary given the prediction &ldquo;the number of students seeking higher education will increase by 70% in the next two decades&rdquo;.\n\nThe Irish Universities Association (IUA) welcomed the report as setting out &ldquo;a strategic framework for the development of Higher Education&rdquo;. They echoed the &ldquo;proposal to develop a system of income contingent loans&rdquo; and for expansion of participation to focus mainly on &ldquo;part time and adult learners, post graduate and international students&rdquo;.\n\nThe College noted that the contents of the report had not been &ldquo;formally discussed by College fora yet&rdquo;, referring the University Times to the statement by the (IUA).\u00a0 &ldquo;many of the recommendations have already been implemented by Trinity already&rdquo;.\n\nStudent reaction was more hostile, with the Union of Students in Ireland saying the recommendations in the report would &ldquo;lead to brain drain and reduction in access to education&rdquo;. Gary Redmond, USI president said while he welcomed many of the recommendations relating to part-time students and standards of teaching, &ldquo;the proposal for a student loan scheme is unworkable, unfeasible and if it is implemented, it will be a regressive step for this country, and will in fact lead to increased exchequer borrowing&rdquo;.\n\nJennifer Fox, education officer for Trinity Students&rsquo; Union, said that &ldquo;while a large amount of the report was positive, there are fundamental flaws linked to a number of the recommendations. I don&rsquo;t believe it was unplanned that many of the progressive suggestions in the report are vague while funding changes are specific.&rdquo;\n\nUnions for staff in third level institutions were more equivocal in their response. IFUT, the Irish Federation of University Teachers welcomed the call for a substantial increase in funding for higher education, but called the report &ldquo;uninspiring&rdquo;.\u00a0 With a change in government imminent, IFUT remarked that &ldquo;Colin Hunt and his team may well have created one of our all-time most expensive dust accumulators&rdquo;\n\nFine Gael said the report illustrated the failures of successive Fianna F\u00e1il governments. Education spokesperson Fergus O&rsquo;Dowd TD claimed Fine Gael were the &ldquo;only political party to set out a comprehensive strategy for reforming third level&rdquo;, and reiterated his party&rsquo;s support for a graduate tax.\n\nRuair\u00ed Quinn TD, Labour spokesperson on education, said the delay in the publication of the report &ldquo;is sadly indicative of the lack of urgency within the Department of Education and Skills to confront a range of important issues&rdquo;. He condemned the report&rsquo;s recommendations on undergraduate fees, saying the conclusions were &ldquo;vague, poorly described, not quantified in any manner and would receive a D mark if submitted as an answer to a Commerce Degree exam&rdquo;.", "Thumb_nail": "http://universitytimes.ie/wp-content/uploads/2013/utlogo.jpg", "ID": "247", "Heading": "Report reactions vary wildly"}